<p>The <b>Lotus Sutra</b> or <i><a href="/wiki/Sutra" title="Sutra" class="mw-redirect">Sutra</a> on the White <a href="/wiki/Sacred_lotus" title="Sacred lotus" class="mw-redirect">Lotus</a> of the Sublime Dharma</i> (Sanskrit: <span lang="sa" xml:lang="sa">सद्धर्मपुण्डरीकसूत्र</span> <i><span lang="sa-Latn" title="International Alphabet of Sanskrit Transliteration" class="Unicode" style="white-space:normal; text-decoration: none" xml:lang="sa-Latn">Saddharma Puṇḍarīka Sūtra</span></i>; <a href="/wiki/Mandarin" title="Mandarin">Mandarin</a>: 妙法蓮華經<i>Miàofǎ Liánhuā Jīng</i>; <a href="/wiki/Japanese_language" title="Japanese language">Japanese</a>: <span lang="ja" xml:lang="ja">Myōhō Renge Kyō</span>; <a href="/wiki/Korean_language" title="Korean language">Korean</a>: <span lang="ko" xml:lang="ko">Myo beom nyeon hwa gyeong</span>; Vietnamese: <i>Diệu Pháp Liên Hoa Kinh</i>) is one of the most popular and influential <a href="/wiki/Mahayana" title="Mahayana">Mahayana</a> sutras in Asia and the basis on which the <a href="/wiki/Tien_Tai" title="Tien Tai" class="mw-redirect">Tien Tai</a> and <a href="/wiki/Nichiren_Buddhism" title="Nichiren Buddhism">Nichiren</a> sects of <a href="/wiki/Buddhism" title="Buddhism">Buddhism</a> were established.</p>
